---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const description =
  "Plain Theory Labs — certification framework for sustainable AI compute infrastructure";
---

<BaseLayout title="Plain Theory Labs — certification framework for sustainable AI compute infrastructure" description={description}>
  <section class="section prose">
    <h1>The infrastructure behind AI is mostly invisible. We are making it legible.</h1>

    <p class="thesis">
      Plain Theory Labs builds certification infrastructure
      for AI compute. We measure what GPU clusters are actually
      doing, score it against a documented methodology, and
      deliver findings that research computing directors can act
      on and sustainability offices can report against.
    </p>

    <p>
      We are AI and HPC systems engineers. We have spent our careers
      inside these systems — configuring schedulers at research
      universities, tuning GPU allocations at academic medical
      centers, reading the telemetry that most organizations
      collect and never fully use. We know what efficient
      infrastructure looks like. We built PTL because no
      independent standard existed to say so.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>What actually happens when you use AI</h2>

    <p>
      Every query sent to a large language model triggers a
      cascade of physical events most people never consider.
      A GPU wakes up and draws between 300 and 700 watts.
      A cooling system compensates for the heat. A power
      infrastructure conditions electricity from the grid.
    </p>

    <p>
      A single A100 running continuously for a year consumes
      roughly <span class="datum">3,500 kWh</span>. A modest research cluster of 100
      GPUs draws more power than a small neighborhood. The
      largest training runs now require facilities measured
      in hundreds of megawatts.
    </p>

    <p>
      This infrastructure exists. It is operating today.
      Its footprint is growing faster than anyone is
      measuring it rigorously.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>The data exists. The grades don't.</h2>

    <p>
      HPC centers run Prometheus, Grafana, DCGM, and Slurm
      accounting. They collect utilization rates, job
      runtimes, power draw, and queue statistics around
      the clock. The data has always been there.
    </p>

    <p>
      What does not exist is a methodology that turns that
      data into a grade. A score that tells an organization
      not just what is happening, but how it compares to
      what is achievable — and what a specific change
      would produce.
    </p>

    <p>
      Without that, monitoring data has no policy weight.
      An HPC director cannot write a procurement requirement
      around a utilization rate with no reference point.
      A sustainability office cannot report against a number
      with no standard. A funding agency cannot evaluate
      an efficiency claim with no independent basis.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>The certification framework</h2>

    <p>
      Seven components. Five analytical engines measure what
      organizations are operating. GRADE scores the findings
      into a certification tier. ATLAS turns the certification
      into a specific action plan.
    </p>

    <div class="findings">
      <p><strong>ACE</strong>Adaptive Compute Efficiency Engine<br>GPU utilization, job efficiency, right-sizing</p>
      <p><strong>COOL</strong>Cooling Operations Optimization Layer<br>PUE efficiency, cooling system performance</p>
      <p><strong>FLUX</strong>Facility Load and Utilization Index<br>Carbon accounting methodology, greenwashing detection</p>
      <p><strong>PACE</strong>Predictive Allocation and Cluster Efficiency<br>Scheduler policy, over-requesting patterns</p>
      <p><strong>CORE</strong>Capital and Operations Resource Evaluator<br>Hardware-workload fit, fleet age, embodied carbon</p>
      <p><strong>GRADE</strong>Granular Rating for AI Data center Efficiency<br>Certification tier: BRONZE through PLATINUM</p>
      <p><strong>ATLAS</strong>Actionable Trajectory and Longitudinal Analysis<br>Ranked recommendations, trajectory projection</p>
    </div>

