</div>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <p>
      The certification runs from MEASURED — a first honest baseline
      recorded before any remediation — through BRONZE, SILVER, GOLD,
      and PLATINUM. Each tier reflects both what was measured and how
      well it scored; coverage and performance are graded separately.
      The first system we assessed was MIT Supercloud, on a
      peer-reviewed public dataset of 73,367 production jobs. Average
      GPU utilization: 25.7%. The top recommendation from ATLAS was
      specific enough to act on the same week.
    </p>

    <a href="/certification" class="cta-link">How certification works →</a>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>Built on real data</h2>

    <p>
      The Adaptive Compute Efficiency Engine is the first of
      five analytical engines in the stack. It ingests Slurm
      scheduler exports, scores every job against a documented
      efficiency methodology, and produces findings with
      confidence labels and fully disclosed assumptions.
    </p>

    <p>
      We validated it on a published, peer-reviewed dataset
      from a production system. The numbers below are not
      projections.
    </p>

    <div class="findings">
      <p>MIT Supercloud HPCA22 dataset — 73,367 production jobs</p>
      <p><strong>25.7%</strong>average GPU utilization</p>
      <p><strong>$255,271</strong>in recoverable savings identified</p>
      <p>MEASURED certification — first honest baseline</p>
    </div>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>Efficiency is a scientific priority</h2>

    <p>
      AI is central to how science gets done today. Drug
      discovery, climate modeling, genomics, and fusion
      research all depend on GPU clusters operating at scale.
    </p>

    <p>
      A cluster running at <span class="datum">15% average GPU utilization</span> is not
      just wasting energy. It is wasting research capacity.
      The most ambitious science should run on the most
      efficiently operated infrastructure. Those two things
      are not in tension.
    </p>

    <p>
      The data to understand this already exists inside
      every HPC center. We provide the methodology to
      make it legible.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>The standard is being written now</h2>

    <p>
      The EU AI Act requires environmental impact assessment
      for high-impact AI systems. Federal AI infrastructure
      spending is under growing scrutiny from appropriators.
      NSF and DOE grant programs are beginning to ask
      sustainability questions they did not ask two years ago.
    </p>

    <p>
      Organizations that engage now will have a tested
      methodology and a documented track record when external
      requirements arrive. The ones that wait will be graded
      against a standard they had no role in building.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>Start a pilot</h2>

    <p>
      We are taking three pilot organizations this quarter.
    </p>

    <p>
      You provide a Slurm scheduler export and answer four
      questions about your facility. We run the analysis and
      deliver a private certification report to your team.
      The data collection takes under two hours.
    </p>

    <p>
      The findings belong to your organization.
      We keep the methodology.
    </p>

    <a href="mailto:jesus@plaintheory.org" class="cta-link">Start a pilot</a>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
